&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Hi Michael,
&gt;
&gt; &lt;biased&gt;
&gt;
&gt; How different is what you have described from
&gt; http://jakarta.apache.org/cactus/1.4/howto_tomcat.html ?
&gt;
&gt; Actually, what you described is exactly JUnitEE
&gt; (http://junitee.sourceforge.net/).
&gt;
&gt; I agree with you, it starts simple and then you need some more features.
&gt; For example, you need to automate the tests as part of a build (this is
&gt; probably one of the most wanted feature). So you will start to have a
&gt; client part that calls your URL, parses the XML and display the result.
&gt; All is fine but then you also want to be able to execute the test from
&gt; any of the existing JUnit integration tools (from IDEs, using Ant junit
&gt; task, etc). So you will transform your client side into a TestCase so
&gt; that it can be run by any test runner ...
&gt;
&gt; ... and this is Cactus ! :-)
&gt;
&gt; To summarise :
&gt;
&gt; - yes Cactus can be a simple as what you describe (this is actually a
&gt; feature of version 1.4, which is not released yet - but soon to be)
&gt;
&gt; - it allow for more should you need it
&gt;
&gt; - it is documented and there are resources on Cactus : website + books +
&gt; articles
&gt;
&gt; - BTW, Cactus integrates completely with Ant to automated start up and
&gt; shutdown of application servers
&gt;
&gt; &lt;/biased&gt;
&gt;
&gt; Yes, I am the original author of Cactus and thus I am biased :-) but as
&gt; a user I would always go with existing framework if I find any that
&gt; perform what I want. For example, I wouldn&#39;t dare write my logging
&gt; framework, MVC controller one, XML to Java mapping one, etc.
&gt;
&gt; In the end it is your choice. I&#39;m just writing this email so that you
&gt; know Cactus does what you want and that you shouldn&#39;t skip it because
&gt; you think it doesn&#39;t.
&gt;
&gt; Cheers,
&gt; -Vincent
&gt;
